# Clinical safety constraints

These are the hard constraints of the product. They are not preferences and they are
not open to optimisation. If a request appears to conflict with one of these, stop and
say so rather than implementing it.

## 1. Deterministic capture

Every question shown to a child or parent is pre-authored and paediatrician-approved,
loaded from `lib/questions/`. No model output is ever rendered in a patient-facing view.

```ts
// ❌ NEVER — generative model between clinician intent and child screen
const kidQuestion = await rephraseForChild(clinicianQuestion);

// ✅ Fixed, authored, looked up by id
const question = STANDARD_QUESTIONS.find((q) => q.id === "pain_present");
```

Clinicians cannot free-type questions for the child. They select from the standard set
plus the approved supplementary library in `lib/questions/supplementary.ts`. Do not add
a free-text question field to the clinician setup UI.

## 2. The summary is a template render, not generated prose

`buildSummary()` is a pure function: structured responses in, structured summary out.
It must contain no network calls and no model involvement.

```ts
// ❌ NEVER
const summary = await claude.summarise(responses);

// ✅
const summary: SessionSummary = buildSummary(responses, session);
```

Parent free text passes through **verbatim**. Never paraphrase, summarise, translate,
or clean it up.

## 3. AI is advisory, downstream, and clinician-gated

The only generative call in the product suggests follow-up questions after the standard
set completes. Rules:

- Suggestions must be selected from or mapped to the approved supplementary library
- Every suggestion carries `source: "ai_suggested"` and renders with a visible label
- A suggestion reaches a patient view **only** after an explicit clinician approve action
- There is no auto-approve, no bulk-approve, no "approve all" button, no config flag
  that bypasses review — do not add one even if asked to "speed up the demo"
- Suggestions are phrased as questions only, never as findings, impressions, or advice

```ts
// Enforce at the type level
type Suggestion = { id: string; text: string; rationale: string; source: "ai_suggested" };
type ApprovedQuestion = Suggestion & { approvedBy: ClinicianId; approvedAt: string };
// Only ApprovedQuestion may be passed to session rendering
```

## 4. LLM calls are server-side only

Anthropic calls live in `app/api/` route handlers. The API key is read from `.env`,
never shipped to the client, never inlined, never placed in a `NEXT_PUBLIC_` variable.

## 5. No clinical logic

This app collects and displays. It does not score, stratify, flag severity, compute
risk, or suggest a diagnosis. If a feature request implies interpretation of symptoms,
flag it rather than building it.

## 6. Provenance is mandatory

Every captured response records who gave it: `"child" | "parent" | "proxy"`. This field
is required in the schema and must be surfaced in the summary. It is clinically
significant and must never be defaulted, inferred, or dropped for convenience.

## 7. Out of scope, deliberately

Safeguarding detection and escalation are not implemented. Do not add keyword scanning,
risk flagging, or alerting on free text. A half-built safeguarding feature is worse than
none. This gap is documented in the PRD.
